,"Frontal and sphenoid","Temporal and occipital","Frontal and parietal"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ethmoid bone is a complex structure located at the roof of the nasal cavity and contributes to the medial wall of the orbit. It articulates with several bones in the skull, including the \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal and sphenoid\u003C/strong\u003E bones. These articulations are important for the structural integrity of the cranial base and the formation of the nasal cavity and orbits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal and zygomatic\u003C/strong\u003E bones do not articulate with the ethmoid bone. The zygomatic bone is primarily associated with the lateral wall of the orbit and the cheekbone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eparietal and temporal\u003C/strong\u003E bones are located on the sides of the skull and do not articulate with the ethmoid bone. They are more involved in forming the cranial vault.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etemporal and occipital\u003C/strong\u003E bones are located at the base and back of the skull, respectively, and do not articulate with the ethmoid bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal and parietal\u003C/strong\u003E bones articulate with each other at the coronal suture but do not both articulate with the ethmoid bone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ethmoid bone articulates with the frontal and sphenoid bones.","Understanding cranial bone articulations is important for comprehending skull anatomy."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64170"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17938"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64170"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T20:02:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T20:02:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10652"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78821"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4899"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-13T1